\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
% ============================================================
 
Social media posts and prediction markets both aggregate information
about real-world events whose outcomes are uncertain, yet they do so
through very different mechanisms.
A single credible post can shift a market's probability estimate
within minutes, trigger correlated moves across dozens of related
contracts, and generate volume spikes that persist for hours.
Once the event resolves, the same posts may supply the decisive
evidence that formally settles the market.
This tight coupling --- from early social signal through price
reaction to formal adjudication --- constitutes a complete
information lifecycle, yet despite active research at the
intersection of social media and event
forecasting~\cite{bollen2011twitter,sprenger2014tweets,ding2014using,
ritterman2009using}, no existing benchmark captures it as a unified
object of study.
 
The gap stems from how current datasets partition the problem.
Social media benchmarks label posts for sentiment or topical
relevance~\cite{rosenthal2017semeval,barbieri2020tweeteval},
discarding the downstream market signal.
Financial forecasting datasets pair prices with news
headlines~\cite{kogan2009predicting,chen2014wisdom}, discarding the
conversational, multimodal character of social posts.
Neither addresses the most fundamental alignment question:
\emph{which prediction market does this post concern, and what does
it imply about that market's future price and ultimate resolution?}
 
We introduce \dataset, which links (1)~a Twitter/X post with text
and optional image or OCR; (2)~a Polymarket question and
resolution rule; (3)~sibling-market context from the same event
graph; and (4)~a fine-grained price--volume time series.
Each instance therefore spans multiple distinct modalities:
natural-language text, images (photographs, charts, and text
screenshots), market price and volume time series, and structured
market metadata (question, resolution rule, category, deadline).
We design six tasks, organized into two tiers, spanning the complete
post-to-market lifecycle (Table~\ref{tab:tasks}).
\emph{Forecast tasks} are grounded in tick data generated after the
post; no model can access this data at inference time, and labels
are computed deterministically by SQL.
\emph{Resolution tasks} are grounded in present-day market metadata
and rules; they demand semantic and evidential reasoning and are
human-annotated.
 
All six tasks are both practically important and technically
challenging.
Forecast tasks require reasoning over social signals, market context,
and time-series data that standard vision--language models are not
designed to handle: predicting volume before any price exists
(\taskname{T1}), directional price movement conditioned on what is
already priced in (\taskname{T4}), cross-market propagation
(\taskname{T6}), and impact persistence (\taskname{T5}).
Resolution tasks pose complementary challenges: fine-grained retrieval
among near-synonymous market candidates (\taskname{T2}) and
legal-style evidence grading against formal written rules
(\taskname{T3}).
Our experiments confirm that all tasks remain substantially open for
current multimodal and language models.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Contributions} of this paper can be summarized as:
 
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.8em, itemsep=1pt, topsep=2pt]
  \item \emph{Dataset.} \dataset comprises
  {11,952} Polymarket markets and {9.0M} KOL posts
  collected over 2021--2026, spanning politics, sports, crypto, and
  entertainment, with image/OCR (37.9\% media rate), event graph,
  and tick data per instance.
  \item \emph{Forecast/resolution taxonomy.} We formalize a
  two-tier task structure whose forecast labels are computed
  deterministically via SQL at zero annotation cost, confining
  human judgment to the two resolution tasks.
  \item \emph{Baselines.} We evaluate text-only, multimodal, and
  market conditioned models on all six tasks, establishing that the
  forecast tasks remain substantially open.
\end{enumerate}
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Potential applications.}
Beyond benchmarking multimodal models, \dataset can support research
in social media--driven financial forecasting, real-time event
detection, misinformation identification through market--post
disagreement, and cross-modal reasoning over text, images, and time
series. Its event-graph structure also enables studies of information
propagation across related markets.

\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Licensing and access.}
\dataset is released under the CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license for
non-commercial research use. Data, task definitions, and evaluation scripts are publicly
available on our Git repo. Polymarket data are redistributed in accordance with the platform's
public API terms, and Twitter/X content is shared as post IDs to
comply with the platform's data redistribution policy. The full Twitter/X data can be requested with a Data Use Agreement.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}
% ============================================================
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Social media and market forecasting.}
Beginning with Bollen~\etal~\cite{bollen2011twitter}, a line of
work spanning event-driven models~\cite{ding2014using,ding2015deep}
and author-credibility graphs~\cite{xu2018stock,sawhney2020deep}
has established that social posts carry predictive market signal.
However, all prior studies evaluate against aggregate returns or
binary up/down labels that are decoupled from each post's specific
claim.
Multimodal extensions incorporate audio~\cite{sawhney2020multimodal}
and cross-asset structure~\cite{sawhney2020deep};
Nofer and Hinz~\cite{nofer2015twitter} further showed that the
strength of the effect depends on feature construction.
\dataset replaces aggregate labels with prediction market prices,
where each price is semantically aligned to the exact proposition
the post addresses.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Prediction markets.}
Prediction markets are validated as probability aggregators on
both theoretical~\cite{wolfers2004prediction} and
empirical~\cite{berg2008results,rothschild2009forecasting,
leigh2006competing} grounds.
Ritterman~\etal~\cite{ritterman2009using} remains the only prior
work linking social posts to prediction market prices, and does so
at aggregate temporal granularity on a single contract; \dataset
provides instance-level alignment across thousands of markets.
Recent work examines Polymarket directly~\cite{tsang2026anatomy}
and studies social network effects on market
efficiency~\cite{qiu2014effects}.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Multimodal misinformation and event understanding.}
Event detection corpora (MAVEN~\cite{wang2020maven},
ACE~\cite{doddington2004ace}) focus on entity annotation without
market outcomes.
Multimedia veracity benchmarks (MediaEval~\cite{boididou2015mediaeval},
NewsCLIPpings~\cite{luo2021newsclippings},
FakeNewsNet~\cite{shu2020fakenewsnet},
Hateful Memes~\cite{kiela2020hateful}) and rumor datasets
(PHEME~\cite{zubiaga2016pheme},
RumourEval~\cite{derczynski2017rumoureval,gorrell2019rumoureval},
DeClarE~\cite{popat2018declare}) cast claim verification as a
text-and-image classification task.
\dataset's \taskname{T3} extends this direction by grounding
evidence grading in a formal written rule and connecting the grade
to downstream market resolution outcomes.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Financial NLP benchmarks.}
FinBERT~\cite{araci2019finbert,yang2020finbert},
BloombergGPT~\cite{wu2023bloomberggpt}, and
FinGPT~\cite{yang2023fingpt} target present-day document
understanding tasks such as FinQA~\cite{chen2021finqa},
TAT-QA~\cite{zhu2021tatqa}, and FLUE~\cite{shah2022flue}.
Lopez-Lira and Tang~\cite{lopezlira2023chatgpt} showed that GPT-4
directional predictions carry only marginal predictive power on
equities.
\dataset shifts the axis from comprehending present-day text to
anticipating future market dynamics driven by social signals.
 
