\subsection{Forecast Tasks}
 
A \emph{confound filter} flags instances where a second
grade-$\geq 3$ post from a different author appears within the
forecast window; flagged instances are excluded from test/val splits.
The filter is fully operative for \taskname{T4}; \taskname{T6}
integration is pending (§\ref{sec:annotation}).
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{T1 --- Conditional Market Volume Prediction.}
Given a pre-market post event group, the model predicts the final
volume percentile of the subsequently created market within its
calendar-month cohort: \texttt{high} ($>$80th), \texttt{moderate}
(40th--80th), or \texttt{low} ($<$40th).
T1 is \emph{conditional}: pipeline analysis reveals that
$\approx$7.7K posts form post-creation bursts, while
$\approx$9.8K constitute recoverable pre-market bursts. The task is
therefore restricted to event groups with detectable pre-market
signal ($\bar{c}>0.70$, composite score $>2.5$;
§\ref{sec:annotation}).
Of the 8,042 event groups constructed (973 linked to a market),
342 candidate markets pass the quality filter; \textbf{326} of these
pass the volume filter ($>$50 trades using final volume),
yielding 109 \texttt{high}, 114 \texttt{moderate}, and
103 \texttt{low} instances (16 thin-market outliers excluded).
The mean volume percentile rank is 0.600 (median 0.639),
confirming that socially salient events attract above-average
trading activity.
Metrics: macro-$F_1$, \texttt{high}-class precision@$K$.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{T4 --- Market Movement Prediction.}
Given post $p$, linked market $m$, and reference price $p_0$ (the
YES-side close price at or immediately before post time $t_p$),
the model predicts direction (\texttt{up} / \texttt{flat} /
\texttt{down}) and magnitude bucket (\texttt{large} / \texttt{medium}
/ \texttt{small}) of price change at the primary horizon
$H = 2\text{h}$, with thresholds $|\Delta p| = 0.02$ and $0.08$;
prices at 30\,min and 6\,h serve as secondary targets.
$p_0$ is a required model input: a bullish post may have zero
impact if the information is already priced in.
Instances with no price tick in the 2-hour window
(\textit{ghost markets}) are excluded, leaving \textbf{4,803} valid
instances (Table~\ref{tab:t4stats}).
A continuous \texttt{horizon\_curve} is also stored for regression.
Metrics: direction accuracy, magnitude macro-$F_1$, Spearman $\rho$.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{T6 --- Cross-Market Propagation.}
For post $p$ linked to market $m$ with sibling set $\mathcal{S}$,
the model predicts whether the post's information propagates to
shift sibling prices within 2 hours.
The sibling graph is constructed in two layers: a rule-based
high-precision layer and an embedding-based recall layer, combined
via pairwise confidence scoring and a noise filter.
A market is deemed \emph{moved} if $|\Delta p| > 1.5\sigma$, where
$\sigma$ is its rolling 24h standard deviation.
Labels: \texttt{primary\_mover} ($m$ moves first, $\geq\!1$ sibling
follows), \texttt{propagated\_signal} (a sibling moves before or
instead of $m$), \texttt{no\_effect}.
The onset lag of each sibling's move is also recorded.
Of 4,006 valid instances (drawn from 1,148 unique primary markets
with usable price windows), 616 (15.4\%) / 799 (19.9\%) / 2,591
(64.7\%) fall into \texttt{primary\_mover} /
\texttt{propagated\_signal} / \texttt{no\_effect}, respectively
(35.3\% exhibit cross-market propagation).
The mean sibling set size is 10.9 (median 9); among moved siblings,
the mean onset lag is 44.4\,min (median 36.0\,min).
Propagation rates vary by domain: politics 37.4\%, crypto 32.8\%,
sports 21.7\%.
T3 confound filtering flags 593 instances (14.8\%); integration
into the final test/dev splits is pending.
Metrics: macro-$F_1$, mean absolute error on onset lag (minutes).
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{T5 --- Volume and Price Impact.}
This task is restricted to posts with a non-flat \taskname{T4}
direction label (\texttt{direction\_label} $\in$
\{\texttt{up}, \texttt{down}\} and \texttt{price\_t0} not null).
The model predicts three targets per post:
(i)~\texttt{price\_impact} ---
$\max_H |\Delta p_H|$ (maximum absolute deviation from $p_0$) over
$H \in \{15\text{m}, 30\text{m}, 1\text{h}, 2\text{h}, 6\text{h}\}$;
(ii)~\texttt{volume\_multiplier} --- total traded volume in
$[t_p,\,t_p{+}H]$ divided by the rolling 24h baseline (mean hourly
volume in $[t_p{-}24\text{h},\,t_p)$); and
(iii)~\texttt{decay\_class}, determined by comparing close prices at
15\,min and 2\,h against $p_0$:
\texttt{transient} if $|\Delta p_{2h}| < 0.3|\Delta p_{15m}|$,
\texttt{sustained} if the move is larger and in the same direction
at 2\,h, and \texttt{reversal} if the sign flips at 2\,h.
Rows missing either $p_{15m}$ or $p_{2h}$ are excluded;
null or non-positive 24h baselines yield null
\texttt{volume\_multiplier}.
The confound filter uses the maximum horizon (6\,h) window;
prices are tracked on the YES side only, consistent with
\taskname{T4}.
Of the 1,338 eligible instances, 407 have complete T5 labels;
among these, 268 are non-confounded.
On the 268 clean instances, the decay distribution is:
\texttt{transient} 51.1\%, \texttt{sustained} 31.3\%,
\texttt{reversal} 17.5\%.
Mean \texttt{price\_impact} is 0.11 (median 0.05) and mean
\texttt{volume\_multiplier} is 10.6 (median 2.56).
Average price impact grows from 0.095 at 15\,min to 0.12 at 2\,h
and 0.14 at 6\,h, indicating that impact accumulates over time.
Metrics: Spearman $\rho$ for the two continuous targets,
\texttt{decay\_class} macro-$F_1$.
 
\section{Dataset}
\label{sec:dataset}
 
\subsection{Data Sources and Collection}
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Polymarket.}
The Polymarket corpus encompasses \textbf{426,357} unique binary
markets collected via the public API and on-chain CLOB contract on
Polygon.
Of these, \textbf{11,952} have price time-series data and form
the usable market universe.
Among resolved markets (11,847 of 11,952), 25.7\% resolve YES and
71.9\% NO --- a skew that reflects the inherent base-rate difficulty
of positive-outcome prediction.
Median market duration is 1.8~days (mean: 9.4~days), a
short-to-medium horizon well suited to near-term event forecasting.
Liquidity is heavily concentrated: the top 1\% of markets account
for 65.2\% of total trading volume.
Per market, we retain: question text, full resolution rule, creation
and resolution timestamps, outcome, 1-minute price and volume time
series, and event graph membership.
Four filters are applied:
(i)~\emph{thin-market} (${<}50$ lifetime trades);
(ii)~\emph{duration} (resolution within 24h of creation);
(iii)~\emph{near-duplicate} (cosine similarity~$>0.92$ to an
existing market);
(iv)~\emph{unresolved} (test/val markets must be fully resolved).
After filtering, {11,952 markets} remain across five domains
(Table~\ref{tab:stats}).
 
Event clusters link markets sharing $\geq\!2$ named entities within
14-day windows (merged transitively), forming the sibling graph used
by \taskname{T6} and \taskname{T2}.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Twitter/X.}
The social corpus comprises {9,036,781} tweets from
{1,152} key opinion leader (KOL) accounts collected over
2021--2026.
KOL selection prioritizes high-visibility accounts with broad event
coverage; the most prolific account contributed 141,706 tweets, while
the median KOL posted 2,850 --- a mean-to-median ratio of 2.75
consistent with power-law participation.
Average post engagement is 2,402 likes, 110 replies, and 160,152
views, confirming broadcast-style influencer activity.
Of all tweets, {37.9\%} contain media; images are
OCR-processed with Tesseract and classified as \emph{text screenshot},
\emph{chart}, or \emph{photograph}.
The corpus is 95.3\% English; non-English content is slightly more
prevalent in sports (6.3\% vs.\ 3.9\% for non-sports), reflecting
the international character of sports discourse.
Post volume is stable at 1.5--2.0M per year from 2021 to 2025.
 
\subsection{Instance Construction}
 
An instance is the tuple $(p,\,m,\,\mathcal{S},\,\mathcal{T})$:
post, linked market, sibling set, and price--volume time series
aligned to the post timestamp.

\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Candidate generation.}
All market questions and post texts are encoded into
1024-dimensional dense vectors using
BGE-large-en-v1.5~\cite{xiao2023cpack} and indexed
over the full market corpus (426K markets) with
FAISS~\cite{johnson2021faiss} \texttt{IndexFlatIP}.
For each post, the top-50 retrieved markets are post-filtered by a
$\pm$6h time window and capped at ten candidates; pairs below
similarity 0.70 ($\approx$96\% of pairs) are discarded, retaining
$\approx$355K pairs for verification.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Linking (\taskname{T2}).}
Each candidate pair is classified by a
Qwen2.5-4B~\cite{qwen2024qwen25} judge
(§\ref{sec:annotation}) as \texttt{PASS}, \texttt{DROP}, or
\texttt{REVIEW}; \texttt{PASS} pairs (342,552) are
auto-accepted, 1,259 \texttt{REVIEW} cases proceed to
human annotators who accepted 815 (0.24\% of retained links), and
\texttt{DROP} pairs (10,751) are discarded.
In total, 343,367 tweet--market links are retained (99.76\% PASS,
0.24\% human-accepted REVIEW);
96.2\% of posts are linked to no market, with an average of
12.0 tweets per linked market.
The mean embedding similarity of accepted pairs is 0.722, and the
average candidate set size per post is 6.58.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Time series alignment.}
We extract the price--volume series over $[t_p{-}30\text{min},\;
t_p{+}6\text{h}]$; $p_0$ is the last tick at or before $t_p$.
Instances with $<$5 ticks are excluded.
 
