\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Baselines.}
We organize baselines into four categories
(Table~\ref{tab:results}).
 
\smallskip\noindent\emph{(i) Trivial.}
\textbf{Majority} always predicts the most frequent class (or the
training-set median for continuous targets).
\textbf{Random} samples from the class prior.
These establish the floor that any informed model must exceed.
 
\smallskip\noindent\emph{(ii) Heuristic / retrieval.}
For \taskname{T2}: \textbf{BGE top-1} returns the highest-scoring
candidate from the BGE-large-en-v1.5~\cite{xiao2023cpack} dense
retrieval index without re-ranking; \textbf{BM25 top-1} replaces
dense retrieval with sparse term-matching (Okapi BM25) over the same
candidate set.
For \taskname{T3}: the deterministic \textbf{pre-check pipeline}
runs four rule-based checks --- source authority (whitelisted
domains/accounts), time condition (post timestamp vs.\ market
deadline), numeric threshold (extracted quantities vs.\ resolution
threshold), and predicate entity match (spaCy NER + token-level
fuzzy matching) --- each returning
\texttt{pass}/\texttt{fail}/\texttt{uncertain}; the final grade is
assigned by hard-coded logic without any LLM stage.
For \taskname{T4}: a \textbf{random-walk} baseline that extracts the
sign of the 30-minute pre-post price change
$\mathrm{sgn}(p_{t_p} - p_{t_p - 30\mathrm{m}})$ and predicts the
same direction at the 2h horizon, ignoring all post content; this
tests whether social signal adds value beyond momentum.
For \taskname{T6}: a \textbf{graph heuristic} that computes cosine
similarity between the BGE embedding of the primary market question
and each sibling, predicting \texttt{primary\_mover} when the
maximum sibling similarity exceeds a threshold tuned on the
validation set.
 
\smallskip\noindent\emph{(iii) Feature-based ML.}
LightGBM classifiers (or regressors for \taskname{T5} continuous
targets) trained on the following hand-crafted feature vector
(13 dimensions; 15 for \taskname{T6}):
\emph{engagement} --- like count, reply count, and view count of
the post;
\emph{author} --- follower count of the posting account;
\emph{market state} --- reference price $p_0$, 24h rolling baseline
volume (mean hourly volume in $[t_p{-}24\text{h},\,t_p)$), and a
one-hot market category (politics, sports, entertainment,
crypto/finance);
\emph{text sentiment} --- the FinBERT~\cite{araci2019finbert}
positive-class probability computed over the post text.
For \taskname{T6}, two additional graph features are appended:
sibling count $|\mathcal{S}|$ and the mean pairwise BGE cosine
similarity among all markets in the sibling set.
Hyperparameters (learning rate, number of leaves, minimum child
samples) are selected via Bayesian optimization on the validation
split.
 
\smallskip\noindent\emph{(iv) LLM API.}
We evaluate GPT-4o~\cite{openai2023gpt4}, Sonnet~4.5,
Grok~4.1, and Qwen3.5 (4B and 27B)~\cite{qwen2024qwen25}
under two prompting regimes.
\textbf{Zero-shot:} the system message defines the task
(e.g., ``You are an evidence-grading assistant\ldots''), followed
by the task-specific input fields --- post text, market question,
resolution rule (for \taskname{T3}), candidate list (for
\taskname{T2}), reference price $p_0$ (for \taskname{T4}/\taskname{T5})
--- and a JSON output schema specifying the required label keys and
allowed values.
\textbf{Few-shot (3-shot):} the same prompt is augmented with three
demonstration examples per class, sampled from the training set and
balanced across classes; demonstrations include both the input fields
and the gold-standard output.
For \taskname{T4} and \taskname{T5}, a \emph{market-conditioned}
variant (\textbf{GPT-4o + prices}) appends the 6h pre-post price
trajectory as a timestamped list of $(t, p_t)$ pairs, enabling the
model to reason about what is already priced in.
For multimodal tasks (\taskname{T2}, \taskname{T3}, \taskname{T4}),
a \textbf{GPT-4o + image} variant passes the post's attached image
media (photographs, charts, infographics --- not video or
screenshots) via GPT-4o's vision input, supplying visual evidence
(embedded charts, letterheads, OCR-resistant text) that is absent
from the post text.
 
 
