\subsection{Main Results}
\label{sec:main_results}
 
Table~\ref{tab:results} reports performance across all six tasks.
We highlight three principal findings.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Forecast tasks remain substantially open.}
On \taskname{T4}, the best model achieves [.] direction accuracy
against a 58.7\% majority-class floor, and Spearman~$\rho$ on the
continuous horizon curve is only [.], indicating that fine-grained
magnitude prediction is far from solved.
On \taskname{T6}, macro-$F_1$ reaches [.] but onset-lag MAE remains
high at [.]\,min, suggesting that models can detect propagation but
cannot yet time it.
\taskname{T5} continuous targets prove especially difficult: the best
$\rho$ for \texttt{price\_impact} is [.] and for
\texttt{volume\_multiplier} is [.].
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Social signal adds value beyond price history.}
On \taskname{T4}, all post-aware models outperform the random-walk
baseline by [.]--[.] points in direction accuracy, confirming that
post content carries information not already encoded in the pre-post
price trajectory.
The market-conditioned variant (GPT-4o + prices) achieves the highest
$\rho$ of [.], indicating that social and market signals are
complementary.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Resolution rules are essential for grading.}
The deterministic pre-check pipeline alone achieves $\kappa = $ [.]
on \taskname{T3}, a competitive interpretable baseline that
highlights structured rule parsing.
 
