\section{Limitations and Future Work}
\label{sec:limitations}
% ============================================================
 
\noindent\textbf{KOL coverage and selection bias.}
The social corpus is drawn from 1,152 curated KOL accounts, which
biases coverage toward high-visibility English-language posters.
Posts from smaller accounts, reply threads, and non-English
communities may carry complementary signal that our corpus misses.
Expanding to a broader, language-diverse author pool --- while
maintaining linkage quality --- is a priority for future versions.
   
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Static author modeling.}
Our baselines treat each post independently, without modeling
author credibility, historical accuracy, or social network
position.
Incorporating author-level features --- such as per-KOL hit rate
on past directional calls --- could improve forecast tasks and
would enable an ``author matters'' analysis.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Fixed evaluation horizons.}
\taskname{T4} and \taskname{T5} evaluate at discrete horizons
(30\,min, 2\,h, 6\,h), but information incorporation is a
continuous process.
Modeling the full price-response curve as a functional regression
target, and evaluating models on time-to-incorporation and
half-life of impact, would better capture the dynamics of social
information flow.
 
\smallskip\noindent\textbf{Future directions.}
Beyond addressing the above limitations, we see three broader
opportunities:
(i)~\emph{agentic trading simulation}, where models must decide
not just what will happen but whether and when to act on a post;
(ii)~\emph{cross-domain transfer}, training on information-rich
domains (politics) and evaluating on noisy ones (crypto) to test
whether social-to-market reasoning generalizes; and
(iii)~\emph{real-time streaming evaluation}, replacing the current
static benchmark with a live leaderboard that ingests new
Polymarket events and KOL posts daily, ensuring perpetual
anti-contamination.
 
% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% ============================================================
We introduce \dataset, a multimodal benchmark covering the full lifecycle of social information in prediction markets, from initial posts and price dynamics to cross-market propagation and final resolution. It includes six tasks across two tiers (forecast and resolution), each tied to temporally distinct sources of truth, providing an empirically validated anti-contamination guarantee. Our results show that social posts add predictive signal beyond price momentum, modalities matter unevenly across tasks, evidence grade tracks downstream price impact, and predictability varies by domain. Still, all forecast tasks remain unsolved: even top models such as GPT-4o leave substantial room for improvement. We release the dataset, evaluation code, and baseline checkpoints to support reproducible research in social media understanding, multimodal reasoning, and financial forecasting

% ============================================================
\section*{Ethical Considerations}
% ============================================================

\dataset is built from public data: Polymarket’s API and on-chain contracts, plus public Twitter/X posts from key opinion leaders. We collect no private messages, protected content, or PII beyond public usernames, and we do not attempt to de-anonymize market participants.
The benchmark is for research only, not financial advice. Although it studies market prediction, its temporal splits and post-hoc labels make it unsuitable for direct live trading without substantial added infrastructure and regulatory compliance. We encourage users to consider misuse risks, including market manipulation, and to follow applicable financial regulations.

